description.text:
Most kossel kits don't come with a decent spool holder, your bed's never 100% level at the start and you need a decent spool holder that's easy to print.

The model's that this is remixed from use far too much plastic, bed volume and a printed bearing which can get noisy :) This is light weight, small & adjustable while also being able to fit almost any kossel I think!, yell out if you need extra length on the arms.

This design uses a old HDD bearing from a toshiba drive it has a 43 mm diameter on the bottom and 25mm on top.

The bungs included slot on top of the bearing, I've got 52mm and 54mm design's, I'm going to update the 52 one to save on plastic and add a label in the future. The bungs may need a slight sand depending on your Kossel's tolerances.

All part's were completely designed in Fusion 360

For best results

From my test's with the standard motor position of the extruder it has a tad bit of binding and you get a little bit of under extrusion when it pulls for more or retracts, this is because of the length and route it has to go, it also makes the spool winding messy eventually if you feed it a bit extra manually because it's no longer under tension of the extruder.

To counter this, I recommend moving the extruder to the top triangle with a new 100cm stepper cable.This gives you the length to move it.

Overall this makes the travel distance as short & straight as possible from the spool, while also making the bowden tube go straight down the middle of the machine giving it the most direct straight path with minimal chance of resistance.

There are many sensor brackets for the Anet A8 available. I designed these simply to have the sensor as close to the nozzle as possible. It is also small and light.
I got the idea of placing the bracket between the heat sink and fan from this design: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1798669. Thanks!

I've enclosed files for a 12mm or 18mm proximity sensor.

Note: The toothed washers that normally come with the sensor are not needed for this bracket.

Please let me know if you have a problem with the design so I can improve it if necessary.

Also please post a picture with comments if you have made one.

Thanks.

Leo

Here are the settings to use with the Skynet3D V2.x Firmware:

Offsets for 12mm sensor:

define X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -22 // X offset: -left +right [of the nozzle]
define Y_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -36 // Y offset: -front +behind [the nozzle]
define Z_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 0 // Z offset: -below +above [the nozzle]

define LEFT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 25
define RIGHT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 195
define BACK_PROBE_BED_POSITION 170
define FRONT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 20

Offsets for 18mm sensor:

define X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -26 // X offset: -left +right [of the nozzle]

define LEFT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 25

I do not mean this in terms of cost, but you are limited in the mater of spool sizes and also the tube can give you too much resistance if the filament has to be pulled over the edge of the tube.

Products create a connection with the user, leading him to think beyond the product itself, and its use when creating new products from others. It's not just about making a new product, it's about changing your thinking about reuse, and demystifying the concept of trash, with 3D design and printing. I am playing tap my Katamari. It's a very simple tapping game, but I grew tired of tapping myself. So I built a machine to tap for me!

I just added a small motor, 9v batter, and a switch, and presto, a tapping machine!

I used the single piston designed by sirmakesalot. I tweaked the piston for the radius of my stylus, and added a small hole in the middle of the Gear Housing Axle for the motor spindle.

Then the stand is hoist it all above your phone.

Ah pistons, the best way to translate rotational movement to vertical movement!

Assembly

The Stylus I used was 7.7mm in outer diameter. So you might need to adjust the Piston Head hole for use with your own design.

I use a small torch lighter to help me assemble the base to the stand as the tolerance is way to tight, but a little shaving and melting made it a really tight fit. I havent done this yet, but test out the exact distance your phone needs to be away from the piston, mark it and screw/bolt it in place (The Piston housing to the stand I mean...).

Was a scrap switch and motor I used, and a 9v Battery with a wire attachment thingy.

description.text:
Think outside the mini bottle
Using 3D printing to reuse plastic bottles

Since the emergence of 3D printing, it has been transforming manufacturing, and the way we deal with it. The project thinks outside the bottle, uses this technology to transform the use of the plastic bottle in a simple way, giving new uses to this product often incorrectly discarded around the world, transforming what was rubbish into useful, functional products, And beautiful Plastic is seen as a big villain, but it's not as bad as they think, and little attitudes like this can help change that negative concept to respect. All products printed on this project use a plastic called PLA (polylactic acid), biodegradable, and made from corn.
Products create a connection with the user, leading him to think beyond the product itself, and its use when creating new products from others. It's not just about making a new product, it's about changing your thinking about reuse, and demystifying the concept of trash, with 3D design and printing. Innovation and technology go hand in hand and can be used to tell a story beyond what is seen, and lies behind the aesthetics of each product, creating a new user experience.

title: E3D V6 + Titan Zonestar Prusa Hotend Mount (Accommodates Bearing Blocks)

description.text:
nakwada's hotend mount was great for me! Unfortunately, it mounted the facing the opposite direction from most other designs out there, so I modded it a bit to allow for a flipped orientation.

Achieved Goals:

  1. Be compatable with bearing blocks instead of just Linear Bearings, like most designs.
  2. Flip the hotend so that the motor is on the left, leaving the filament tensioning screw to be on the right, which seems more standard.
  3. Lower the whole hotend, since the nozzle did not reach low enough on the original design.
  4. Work with Isograph's cooling fan mount.

I made this to work with my Afinbot A3 Prusa i3 clone.

I made two designs: one that doesn't need many supports, and one that does. I only printed the one that doesn't need supports. I made the other design because the top of the mount made it hard to manually turn the gear that extrudes filament. Since that bit of the model isn't actually important (it's only there to save supports) I removed it. I haven't tried printing the other design, but I would recommend trying that one first.

Note: Both designs lack any supports on the bits where the mount hold the belts. I used Simplify3D, so I had no issues putting little supports there. Other than that, the other bits shouldn't need supports (except for the bottom of the "needs supports" model).

Note: There's one hole inside the spacing rectangles for a screw to go through to attach one of the linear bearing blocks. I made the hole bigger, but on my original design it did not fit my screws. I assume it shouldn't break my design in any way, but if it still isn't large enough let me know so I can make it bigger.

I just used Blender to quickly move around bits of nakwada's design. I've attached the blender file. It's got the original, and some oriented versions I used along the way. Feel free to ask any questions you might have about it!

This is a christmas tree i made in Solidworks and assembled. The STL files are outputted and printed on makerbot. You can import all the parts into the print software. Just import the parts into the software first. Once you import all the parts, it will align the parts correctly. I have also included some holes on the second and third tier so that you can print out some ornaments to hang or tie some candy canes at the end. Tree is printed quite solid as my settings has a 3 shell printout with 10%. You can use 2 shells.

Import into your print software and print out the pieces individually. Otherwise you can import all the pieces into one single piece and print as a whole. However, you will need to enable supports. The individual parts are designed to print individually without any supports.   
Also, printing out individually allows you to use different colors to print the various pieces. The holes on the 2nd and 3rd tier allows you to hang some ornaments. You can print out or tie some candy canes.
